Performance, Infrastructure, and Integration
--------------------------------------------

As for Gemini itself, the only product that has been released so far is an =
updated Bard, which used Gemini Pro (the =E2=80=9Cmiddle=E2=80=9D model in =
terms of capabilities); ArsTechnica put it through its (subjective) paces (=
 https://arstechnica.com/ai/2023/12/chatgpt-vs-google-bard-round-2-how-does=
-the-new-gemini-model-fare/ ) :

When comparing the old Google Bard to the new, Gemini-powered version, ther=
e has been clear progress in the quality of Google=E2=80=99s AI-generated o=
utput. In our math, summarization, factual retrieval, and creative writing =
prompts, Google=E2=80=99s system has shown marked improvement in the eight =
months since we last tested it.

Overall, though, ChatGPT is still the winner in our non-scientific tests; O=
penAI=E2=80=99s system edged out Bard on three prompts, while Bard was only=
 the clear winner in one. But the results were a lot closer than they were =
back in April, as evidenced by the two prompts we judged as ties and the on=
e =E2=80=9Csplit decision=E2=80=9D (depending on whether you compare Gemini=
 to the free GPT-3.5 or the paid GPT-4 Turbo).

Honestly, this is all fine: these are early days in the grand arc of AI, an=
d I see no reason for Google to run from these results=C2=A0=E2=80=94 remem=
ber, as I noted above, this test was done with their =E2=80=9Cmiddle=E2=80=
=9D model:

As for that Ultra model, Google did release a bunch of test results ( https=
://blog.google/technology/ai/google-gemini-ai/#performance ) that, unsurpri=
singly, showed Ultra stacking up quite well relative to GPT-4. Again, thoug=
