Comparing Google=E2=80=99s Tensor chip to Apple A-series seems like an obvi=
ous thing to do, but it=E2=80=99s actually much less comparable than it see=
ms; the Tensor system-on-a-chip (SoC) consists of:

* Two high-performance Cortex-X1 cores
* Two mid-performance Cortex-A76 cores
* Four low-performance Cortex-A55 cores
* A Mali-G78 MP20 (20 core) GPU
* A custom Tensor Processing Unit (TPU)
* Custom image processing units

Only the last two items on this list are unique to Google; the first four a=
re all off-the-shelf ARM designs. This is in contrast to Apple=E2=80=99s A-=
series of chips in which everything is custom, including the high performan=
ce cores, low performance cores, and GPU, in addition to the neural engine =
and image processing units (Apple used off-the-shelf ARM designs for the CP=
U and PowerVR designs for the GPU for the A4 and A5, started using its own =
custom CPU cores in the A6, and its own custom GPU cores in the A11). In ot=
her words, Google has a very long ways to go before they are investing at a=
 level comparable to Apple.

That is correct in terms of CPU/GPU performance; Gemini Nano, though, defin=
itely helps make the case that Google was correct to only worry about addin=
g its TPU unit to a bog-standard chip. That gives Google the advantage in i=
ntegration: they build the model and the TPU, which means they get on-devic=
e performance now, even as Apple is just trying to get its GPUs on board wi=
th models other companies built. It=E2=80=99s a striking reversal of the la=
st decade of software and hardware integration.

